  , issueCommentBody =
      "I agree that for 2.0 we should fix `branch`, `and`, `or`, and `not` and leave everything else as is. I also agree that it will take care of 90% of problems with relatively little work.\r\n\r\nFor semantics, I like what @danielmewes posted:\r\n\r\n```\r\nr.or(\"a\", \"b\", \"c\") -> \"a\"\r\nr.or(\"a\", \"b\", undefined) -> \"a\"\r\nr.or(undefined, \"a\", \"b\") -> \"a\"\r\nr.or(undefined, undefined, undefined) -> undefined\r\n  (Note: the error message of the third `undefined` in the argument list is used)\r\nr.or(false, false, undefined) -> undefined\r\nr.or(undefined, false, false) -> undefined\r\n\r\nr.and(\"a\", \"b\", \"c\") -> \"c\"\r\nr.and(\"a\", \"b\", undefined) -> undefined\r\nr.and(undefined, \"a\", \"b\") -> undefined\r\nr.and(undefined, false, \"b\") -> false\r\nr.and(false, undefined, \"b\") -> false\r\nr.and(undefined, undefined, undefined) -> undefined\r\n  (Note: the error message of the third `undefined` in the argument list is used)\r\nr.and(true, true, undefined) -> undefined\r\nr.and(undefined, true, true) -> undefined\r\n```\r\n\r\nI believe this actually *is* JavaScript semantics. I also don't think we should allow people to turn this off -- I think we should pick a model and stick with it.\r\n\r\nI'm not sure how `branch` and `not` fits into this -- we should find a way to treat non-existence in `branch` and `not` that's consistent with `or` and `and` above."
  , issueCommentId = 73595456
